<div id="review_207495517" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/207495517" />
    <a title="Jen Bracken-Hull" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5497852-jen-bracken-hull"><img alt="Jen Bracken-Hull" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524198699p2/5497852.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/207495517?book_show_action=true">Sep 11, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jen Bracken-Hull" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jen Bracken-Hull" href="/user/show/5497852-jen-bracken-hull">Jen Bracken-Hull</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer207495517" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3423305027542802318">I debated on 1 or 2 stars for this one, but I can&apos;t, in good conscience, give it 2. The more I read, the more I hated. Though it has it&apos;s good points (trying to remember what they are right now), I couldn&apos;t help but feel Abbey&apos;s memoirs are a ruthless and pathetic attempt to personify the West. He is disdainful towards almost everyone: tourists, the government, &quot;Indians&quot;, women. <br/><br/>His depiction of &quot;the Navajo&quot; was particularly distasteful. I understand it was published in 1968, so it&apos;s outdated, b</span>
  <span id="freeText3423305027542802318" style="display:none">I debated on 1 or 2 stars for this one, but I can't, in good conscience, give it 2. The more I read, the more I hated. Though it has it's good points (trying to remember what they are right now), I couldn't help but feel Abbey's memoirs are a ruthless and pathetic attempt to personify the West. He is disdainful towards almost everyone: tourists, the government, "Indians", women. <br /><br />His depiction of "the Navajo" was particularly distasteful. I understand it was published in 1968, so it's outdated, but his ignorance is overwhelming. Why in the world he feels he is qualified to define what a "real Indian" is, is beyond me. Admittedly, he discusses the history and struggles of the Navajo (especially as related to the U.S. government) somewhat eloquently, but his analysis is wrongheaded. He paints the Navajo pre-intervention as "noble savage". The word that best summarizes his description of the Navajo today is "squalor". What? Admittedly there are struggles, and VERY serious ones. But despite what Abbey believes, Navajo culture is well, alive, and helping it's people find security and meaning even in the midst of oppression. Despite what Abbey may think, Navajos are the most qualified and capable of finding solutions to their own problems.<br /><br />The absolute WORST part is when he accuses the Navajo of breeding themselves into oblivion. The remedy, scarily, is making birth control COMPULSORY. This is especially scary when one considers that his wish has been somewhat fulfilled by the uninformed sterilizations of thousands of Navajo women throughout the years. Ick, ick, ick.<br /><br />I found his tolerance for Mormons surprising, but also patronizing. His description of what Mormons achieved in the west is full of admiration, but when it comes to mormons themselves, it's clear they are mostly funny little people in his worldview. There's also a really weird part of either misunderstood or deliberately altered Mormon theology. A friend's wife says she has "bound" herself to Abbey and will take him to heaven with her? It's true Mormons believe they can be "sealed" (mormons say sealed, not bound) to family members and can be with them when they die, but being sealed or "bound" to an acquaintance or friend isn't even part of mormon folklore, let alone doctrine. It is possible, I suppose, that this woman is a headcase, but even so, this excerpt is a misrepresentation of mormons at large and their beliefs.<br /><br />Do yourself a favor and skip Abbey's analyses for some more accurate and palatable Western reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3423305027542802318" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


